<HEADLINE>
<P>
JUDGMENTS ON THE KCBS 'OFFICE ROMANCE' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When Bree Walker says "I don't think it has anything to do with my 
news-gathering abilities . . ." in defense of her apparent adulterous actions, 
it reminds me of Gary Hart. 
</P>
<P>
He used the same words in a vain attempt to defend his ability to run the 
country after being accused by the press and finally admitting the adultery 
during a presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
It's time the Fourth Estate stopped having it both ways. If you are going to 
call politicians to judgment on moral grounds, you must open yourselves to 
moral scrutiny. 
</P>
<P>
If I have a right to know the integrity of my political representatives as 
defined by their personal lives, I have a right to know the same of my 
journalistic representatives. 
</P>
<P>
After all, the fact is that journalists have as much influence as politicians 
over the life of the average citizen. 
</P>
<P>
BARRY COLMAN, Long Beach 
