Regulators Urge Expanded SEC Powers: Three top federal regulators said they 
favor sharply expanding the Securities and Exchange Commission's power over 
securities markets by handing it control of stock futures now handled by 
commodities regulators. In testimony before the Senate Banking Committee, 
Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan, SEC Chairman Richard C. Breeden 
and Treasury Undersecretary Robert Glauber said stripping the Commodity Futures 
Trading Commission of jurisdiction over stock index futures could prove 
beneficial to the long-term health of U.S. markets. 
