<P>
VALVANO PAID HIM AT IONA, EX-NBA CENTER ALLEGES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PHILADELPHIA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Former NBA center Jeff Ruland said he took unspecified amounts of money from 
Jim Valvano while the North Carolina State coach was at Iona, the Philadelphia 
Daily News reported today. 
</P>
<P>
Valvano, who left Iona for N.C. State in 1980, denied Ruland's allegation 
through attorney Art Kaminsky, who also said an NCAA investigation found no 
wrongdoing at Iona. 
</P>
<P>
"Jim doesn't want to get into a public debate over this," Kaminsky told the 
paper. "He doesn't want this to Ping-Pong back and forth." 
</P>
<P>
Ruland, a two-time All-Star with Washington, said, "Greenbacks changed hands." 
</P>
<P>
"I took money from Valvano," the newspaper quoted Ruland as saying. 
</P>
<P>
Asked if he accepted money from Valvano while being recruited or while playing 
at Iona, Ruland said, "Both of those. That's enough. That's all I want to say." 
</P>
<P>
Ruland said the matter wasn't "about a lot of money," but he would not specify 
the amount or say how frequently it changed hands. 
</P>
<P>
"I don't know anything about it," Kaminsky said. "If that's what he wants to 
say, fine." 
</P>
<P>
Ruland's NBA career ended after a knee injury limited his play to five games 
with the Philadelphia 76ers in 1986-87. 
</P>
